---
import Article from '../../layouts/Article.astro';
import Fig from '../../components/Fig.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import DataTable from '../../components/DataTable.astro';
import FaqBlock from '../../components/FaqBlock.astro';
import CtaButton from '../../components/CtaButton.astro';
import { getRebates } from '../../lib/data';
import { dollarsPerUsableKwh, formatAud } from '../../lib/rebate';

const rebates = getRebates();
const perKwhBattery = dollarsPerUsableKwh(rebates);

/** Illustrative STC maths for panels — deeming & zone from CER methodology; STC $ from same net assumption as batteries. */
const panelKw = 6.6;
const zoneRating = 1.382; // zone 3 illustrative
const deemingYears = 2030 - 2026; // remaining deeming to program end year for illustration
const stcPrice = rebates.stcPrice.netAssumed;
const panelStcs = Math.floor(panelKw * zoneRating * deemingYears);
const panelRebate = panelStcs * stcPrice;

const faq = [
  {
    question: 'Is the solar panel rebate the same as the battery rebate?',
    answer:
      'No. Panels create STCs under the Small-scale Renewable Energy Scheme with zone ratings and a deeming period. Batteries under the Cheaper Home Batteries Program use a different STC factor and, since May 2026, capacity tiers. They are separate instruments that can both appear on a combined quote.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Why does my installer quote fewer STCs than last year?',
    answer:
      'The deeming period shrinks as we approach 2030, so a system installed later creates fewer certificates even at the same kilowatt size and zone. Certificate spot prices also move.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which zone am I in?',
    answer:
      'The Clean Energy Regulator publishes the zone map used for STC calculations. Coastal WA, much of NSW and QLD, and other high-insolation areas sit in higher zones than southern Tasmania. Your installer should state the zone on the quote.',
  },
];

const description = `How the solar panel STC rebate works in Australia — zones, deeming to 2030, and a ${panelKw} kW worked example. Separate from the battery program (about $${perKwhBattery.toFixed(0)}/kWh tier 1).`;
---

<Article
  title="Solar rebate for panels: STCs explained"
  description={description}
  crumbs={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'Solar rebate' }]}
  updated="2026-07-12"
  verified={rebates.meta.lastVerified}
>
  <Fragment slot="toc">
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#how">How panel STCs work</a></li>
      <li><a href="#zones">Zone ratings</a></li>
      <li><a href="#deeming">Deeming to 2030</a></li>
      <li><a href="#example">6.6 kW example</a></li>
      <li><a href="#battery">Relationship to batteries</a></li>
      <li><a href="#sources">Sources</a></li>
    </ul>
  </Fragment>

  <p>
    The household “solar rebate” on panels is not a cheque from a single government form — it is usually
    a point-of-sale discount funded by Small-scale Technology Certificates (STCs). Your installer creates
    certificates based on system size, your climate zone, and the remaining deeming period to{' '}
    <Fig>2030</Fig>, then assigns their value against the invoice. It is a different instrument from the
    Cheaper Home Batteries Program, which currently works out to about{' '}
    <Fig>{formatAud(perKwhBattery)}</Fig> per usable kWh in tier 1 for batteries.
  </p>

  <h2 id="how">How panel STCs work</h2>
  <p>
    In plain terms: eligible small-scale solar creates a number of STCs. Those certificates trade in a
    market. Installers typically bundle the expected certificate value into your quote as a discount.
    Headline certificate prices and what you actually receive can differ after brokerage and admin — the
    same reason we use a net STC assumption of <Fig>{formatAud(stcPrice)}</Fig> on battery maths.
  </p>

  <h2 id="zones">Zone ratings</h2>
  <p>
    Australia is split into STC zones. Higher zones (stronger solar resource) create more certificates per
    kilowatt. A <Fig>6.6</Fig> kW system in a high zone is worth more in STCs than the same array in a
    lower zone. Always check which zone the quote uses; it should match the CER map for your postcode.
  </p>

  <h2 id="deeming">Deeming period decline to 2030</h2>
  <p>
    STCs for panels are “deemed” for the years of generation expected to <Fig>2030</Fig>. Each year that
    passes, a new install has fewer deeming years left, so certificate counts fall even if panel prices
    and zone ratings stay put. That gradual decline is built into the scheme design — not a surprise fee.
  </p>
  <Callout type="note" title="Illustrative maths only">
    <p>
      The worked example below uses a zone-3-style rating and remaining deeming years from 2026 to 2030.
      Your postcode zone and exact deeming factor must come from the CER calculation your installer runs.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="example">Worked example: {panelKw} kW in zone 3</h2>
  <DataTable
    caption="Illustrative STC discount for a 6.6 kW rooftop system"
    headers={['Input', 'Value']}
    rows={[
      ['System size', `${panelKw} kW`],
      ['Illustrative zone rating', String(zoneRating)],
      ['Deeming years used here', String(deemingYears)],
      ['STCs (floored)', String(panelStcs)],
      ['Assumed net $/STC', formatAud(stcPrice)],
      ['Illustrative discount', formatAud(panelRebate)],
    ]}
    numericCols={[1]}
  />
  <p>
    Rough formula used here: floor(kW × zone rating × deeming years) × net STC price. Replace zone rating
    and deeming with the live CER figures on your quote. For typical installed cost bands, see{' '}
    <a href="/costs/6-6kw-solar-system-cost/">6.6 kW solar system cost</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="battery">Relationship to the battery program</h2>
  <p>
    Panel STCs and the battery rebate are <strong>separate but combinable</strong> on a solar-plus-battery
    job when each technology meets its own rules. Do not let a quote mash them into one unexplained
    “government discount” line. Ask for panel STC value and battery Cheaper Home Batteries value as
    distinct rows — then check the battery line with our{' '}
    <a href="/battery-rebate/calculator/">calculator</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <CtaButton href="/costs/6-6kw-solar-system-cost/">See 6.6 kW cost guide</CtaButton>
  </p>

  <h2 id="sources">Sources</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href="https://www.cleanenergyregulator.gov.au/RET/Scheme-participants-and-industry/Power-stations">
        Clean Energy Regulator — small-scale scheme
      </a>
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={rebates.meta.sourceUrl}>{rebates.meta.program}</a> (batteries — separate)
    </li>
  </ul>

  <FaqBlock items={faq} />
</Article>
